1	//! Graph GENERATION (BEHAVIOR.md §4, §6): mapping a proof-state / constraint-system
2	//! description onto the DOT [`Graph`] model, over an independent input model
3	//! designed from observed paired `main/proof` sequents and `interactive-graph-def`
4	//! graphs.
5	//!
6	//! What the observed system→graph mapping does, structurally (each point traces to
7	//! corpus/live observation — see BEHAVIOR.md §4, §6):
8	//!   * a **rule instance** `#t : Rule[actions]` becomes a `record` node with up to
9	//!     three groups `{premises}|{info}|{conclusions}`; the **info** group (the
10	//!     `#t : Rule[…]` cell) is always present (100 % of 160 409 corpus records),
11	//!     and an **empty** premise or conclusion group is dropped (so a source rule
12	//!     with no premises renders `{info}|{concl}`);
13	//!   * an intruder-knowledge fact renders as a gray `!KU( m ) @ #t` **ellipse**;
14	//!     a protocol action/event as a darkblue `Fact @ #t` ellipse; a compressed
15	//!     intruder rule as an uncolored `#t : rule` ellipse; a bare **timepoint**
16	//!     (`#i`, `#decrypt`, the designated `#last`) as an uncolored `#var` ellipse;
17	//!   * an unresolved node referenced by an open premise renders as an
18	//!     **invtrapezium** `(#var, idx)` (BEHAVIOR.md §3d);
19	//!   * a **role**-annotated record (role ≠ `Undefined`) is packed into a
20	//!     `subgraph "cluster_<Role>_Session_<k>"` block; role-annotated theories emit
21	//!     the compact header and free (non-role) nodes stay at the top level, in id
22	//!     order, *before* every cluster (BEHAVIOR.md §4);
23	//!   * **edges** connect a conclusion port to a premise port (structural), or an
24	//!     intruder deduction (red dashed), message (gray30), temporal order (blue3 /
25	//!     black dashed), etc. — the finite observed style vocabulary (§3c);
26	//!   * `n<K>` ids come from [`super::alloc`]; record-cell text is wrapped/escaped
27	//!     by [`super::render::wrap_cell`]; the header is inferred by role (§4).
28	//!
29	//! Two cell-content input paths, both flowing through the same wrap/escape
30	//! pipeline: [`RuleInstance`] carries [`Fact`]s (this crate renders + wraps them),
31	//! and [`RawRule`] carries PRE-RENDERED cell strings (the consumer's own printer
32	//! produced them; this crate still wraps and escapes). GAPS (need the GPL solver;
33	//! not derivable from output): *which* nodes/edges/clusters a raw constraint system
34	//! yields, the per-rule/per-cluster color hash, and the accumulated-column wrap
35	//! trigger for cells deep on a record line (BEHAVIOR.md §3f).
